{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":21775,"record_hash":"sha256:45ac33dd89d4b3fa2f60cbe349442e58d4b08b77fcb6867a27bd57d36bbd5639","timestamp":"2026-05-10T21:06:59.145Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"For **session-level correlation**, yes, the shape is enough.\n\nFor **record-level or hunk-level correlation**, no, not yet.\n\nRight now the session data is intentionally project-scoped and branch-agnostic:\n\n```text\nproject\n  gitbutler:agent-sessions = set<session-key>\n  gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:transcript = [...]\n```\n\nThat means a future PR/code-review feature should not try to infer ownership from transcript fields. Instead, when GitButler knows a branch/change/PR is related to a session, it should write a relationship:\n\n```text\n<branch/change/pr target>\n  gitbutler:agent-sessions = set<session-key>\n```\n\nThen the PR view can do:\n\n1. read PR/branch/change relationship set\n2. resolve session keys on the project target\n3. render the full transcript timelines\n\nThat supports:\n\n- one PR with multiple sessions\n- one session associated with multiple branches/PRs\n- sessions that happened before any code was written\n\nWhat we **cannot** do from the current data alone is answer: “this exact transcript record caused this exact hunk/commit.” We store transcript order, timestamps, source keys, roles, content, tool names, and redacted source records, but no branch, commit, hunk, file-change, or PR identifiers.\n\nI think that is okay for the POC. For the code-review use case, session-level association is the right first target. Precise record-to-code correlation can come later if the product needs it, probably as separate relationship metadata rather than stuffing branch/PR fields into transcript records.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-10T21:06:59.145Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","